{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: A/B Testing a Call to Action\n",
        "subtitle: \"Simulating Key Ideas from Classical Frequentist Statistics\"\n",
        "author: \"Qianhui Hong\"\n",
        "date: today\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "I run a website where visitors can subscribe to a newsletter on the homepage. I want to increase the number of sign-ups, so I am considering changing the wording of the call to action (CTA).\n",
        "\n",
        "I create two different versions of the CTA. One says “Sign up for our newsletter here!”, and the other says “Join us to stay updated!”. Although the difference is small, the wording may influence whether users decide to subscribe.\n",
        "\n",
        "To determine which version performs better, I run an A/B test. In an A/B test, visitors are randomly assigned to one of the two versions, so that each group is comparable and not biased by user characteristics. I then compare the sign-up rates between the two groups to see which CTA leads to more conversions. This allows me to make a data-driven decision instead of relying on guesswork.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## The A/B Test as a Statistical Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "From a statistical perspective, we can think about this A/B test in a more formal way. Each visitor either signs up for the newsletter or does not, so the outcome for each person can be represented as either 1 (sign up) or 0 (no sign up). This type of outcome can be modeled using a Bernoulli distribution, where the parameter $\\pi$ represents the probability of signing up.\n",
        "\n",
        "Since the CTA that a visitor sees may influence their behavior, we allow this probability to differ between the two groups. Visitors who see CTA A have a probability of signing up denoted by $\\pi_A$, while those who see CTA B have probability $\\pi_B$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The main quantity we care about is the difference between these two probabilities, which we define as $\\theta = \\pi_A - \\pi_B$. This tells us how much better one CTA performs compared to the other.\n",
        "\n",
        "In practice, we do not know the true values of $\\pi_A$ and $\\pi_B$, so we estimate them using data. Because each observation is either 0 or 1, the sample mean in each group is simply the proportion of visitors who signed up. Therefore, our estimator of $\\theta$ is the difference in sample means, $\\hat\\theta = \\bar{X}_A - \\bar{X}_B$.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Simulating Data\n",
        "\n",
        "In real-world A/B testing, we do not know the true values of $\\pi_A$ and $\\pi_B$. We only observe the data and try to estimate them. However, for the purpose of this exercise, we will set these values ourselves so that we can better understand how our estimator behaves when we know the true difference.\n",
        "\n",
        "Specifically, we assume that $\\pi_A = 0.22$ and $\\pi_B = 0.18$, which means the true difference between the two CTAs is $\\theta = 0.04$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Using this setup, I simulate 1,000 observations for each group from their respective Bernoulli distributions. This gives a total of 2,000 observations, which I will use in the following sections to analyze the performance of the estimator."
      ],
      "id": "0eddc8f7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "np.random.seed(123)\n",
        "\n",
        "A = np.random.binomial(1, 0.22, 1000)\n",
        "B = np.random.binomial(1, 0.18, 1000)"
      ],
      "id": "85274fed",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## The Law of Large Numbers\n",
        "\n",
        "The Law of Large Numbers tells us that as the sample size increases, the sample mean will get closer to the true population mean. In our setting, this means that our estimator $\\hat\\theta = \\bar{X}_A - \\bar{X}_B$ should become more accurate as we observe more data.\n",
        "\n",
        "To illustrate this, I use the simulated data from the previous section. I first compute the difference between each pair of observations from CTA A and CTA B, and then calculate the cumulative average of these differences. This gives a running estimate of $\\hat\\theta$ as the sample size increases from 1 to 1,000.\n",
        "\n",
        "The plot shows that when the number of observations is small, the estimate is quite unstable and fluctuates a lot. However, as more observations are included, the estimate gradually becomes more stable and converges toward the true value of $\\theta = 0.04$.\n",
        "\n",
        "This demonstrates why having a larger sample size is important in A/B testing. With more data, our estimates become more reliable, and we can be more confident that the results reflect the true underlying difference rather than random variation."
      ],
      "id": "6ac160a9"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "diff = A - B\n",
        "\n",
        "cum_avg = np.cumsum(diff) / np.arange(1, len(diff)+1)\n",
        "\n",
        "#| echo: false\n",
        "plt.plot(cum_avg)\n",
        "plt.axhline(0.04, linestyle='--')\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Number of Observations\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Running Estimate of Theta\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Law of Large Numbers in Action\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "19d71eb7",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Bootstrap Standard Errors\n",
        "\n",
        "Now that we have an estimate of $\\hat\\theta$, the next question is how precise this estimate is. In other words, we want to understand how much uncertainty there is around our estimate and construct a confidence interval.\n",
        "\n",
        "One way to measure this uncertainty is through bootstrapping. The bootstrap is a resampling method that does not rely on a specific formula. Instead, we repeatedly draw samples (with replacement) from our observed data and recompute the statistic each time. The variation across these resampled estimates gives us an idea of how much our estimator fluctuates.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this case, I repeatedly resample 1,000 observations from each group and compute $\\hat\\theta^* = \\bar{X}_A^* - \\bar{X}_B^*$ for each resample. After repeating this process 1,000 times, I obtain a distribution of bootstrapped estimates. The standard deviation of these values is the bootstrapped standard error.\n",
        "\n",
        "To check whether this result is reasonable, I also compute the analytical standard error using the formula for the difference in proportions. Comparing the two results helps verify that the bootstrap method provides a consistent estimate of uncertainty.\n",
        "\n",
        "Finally, I use the bootstrapped standard error to construct a 95% confidence interval for $\\theta$, which gives a range of plausible values for the true difference in sign-up rates."
      ],
      "id": "81e1d8e8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "pA = np.mean(A)\n",
        "pB = np.mean(B)\n",
        "\n",
        "boot_theta = []\n",
        "\n",
        "for _ in range(1000):\n",
        "    A_star = np.random.choice(A, size=1000, replace=True)\n",
        "    B_star = np.random.choice(B, size=1000, replace=True)\n",
        "    theta_star = np.mean(A_star) - np.mean(B_star)\n",
        "    boot_theta.append(theta_star)\n",
        "\n",
        "boot_theta = np.array(boot_theta)\n",
        "\n",
        "boot_se = np.std(boot_theta)\n",
        "\n",
        "nA = len(A)\n",
        "nB = len(B)\n",
        "\n",
        "analytical_se = np.sqrt(\n",
        "    (pA * (1 - pA)) / nA +\n",
        "    (pB * (1 - pB)) / nB\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "boot_se, analytical_se"
      ],
      "id": "25114cc1",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## The Central Limit Theorem\n",
        "\n",
        "The Central Limit Theorem (CLT) states that regardless of the shape of the underlying distribution, the sampling distribution of the sample mean becomes approximately Normal as the sample size increases. In our case, this means that the distribution of $\\hat\\theta = \\bar{X}_A - \\bar{X}_B$ will approach a Normal distribution when the sample size is large enough.\n",
        "\n",
        "To illustrate this, I simulate the distribution of $\\hat\\theta$ under different sample sizes. For each value of $n \\in \\{25, 50, 100, 500\\}$, I repeatedly draw samples from the CTA A and CTA B distributions, compute $\\hat\\theta$, and repeat this process 1,000 times. This produces 1,000 estimates of $\\hat\\theta$ for each sample size, which I visualize using histograms.\n",
        "\n",
        "From the plots, we can see that when the sample size is small (such as $n=25$), the distribution of $\\hat\\theta$ is irregular and somewhat noisy. As the sample size increases, the distribution becomes smoother and more symmetric. By the time $n=500$, the histogram looks much closer to a bell-shaped curve.\n",
        "\n",
        "This pattern clearly demonstrates the Central Limit Theorem in action. As the sample size grows, the distribution of our estimator becomes more predictable and approximately Normal, which allows us to use Normal-based methods for inference."
      ],
      "id": "4b35682f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "sample_sizes = [25, 50, 100, 500]\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))\n",
        "\n",
        "for i, n in enumerate(sample_sizes):\n",
        "    thetas = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    for _ in range(1000):\n",
        "        A_sample = np.random.binomial(1, 0.22, n)\n",
        "        B_sample = np.random.binomial(1, 0.18, n)\n",
        "        theta_hat = np.mean(A_sample) - np.mean(B_sample)\n",
        "        thetas.append(theta_hat)\n",
        "\n",
        "    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)\n",
        "    plt.hist(thetas, bins=30)\n",
        "    plt.title(f\"n = {n}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "74171f6a",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Hypothesis Testing\n",
        "\n",
        "Now that we have seen from the Central Limit Theorem that the sampling distribution of $\\hat\\theta$ is approximately Normal for large samples, we can use this result to perform a formal hypothesis test.\n",
        "\n",
        "The goal of a hypothesis test is to determine whether the observed difference between the two CTAs is statistically meaningful or could have occurred by random chance. We start by setting up two hypotheses. The null hypothesis is $H_0: \\theta = 0$, which means that the two CTAs have the same sign-up rate. The alternative hypothesis is $H_1: \\theta \\neq 0$, which means that there is a difference between the two.\n",
        "\n",
        "To carry out the test, we standardize our estimate $\\hat\\theta$ by dividing it by its standard error. This gives the test statistic:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$z = \\frac{\\hat\\theta - 0}{SE(\\hat\\theta)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The reason we do this is based on the CLT. First, we know that $\\hat\\theta$ is approximately Normally distributed when the sample size is large. Under the null hypothesis, its mean is 0. When we divide a Normal random variable by its standard deviation, we obtain a standard Normal distribution. Therefore, under $H_0$, the test statistic $z$ approximately follows a standard Normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is important because it allows us to compute a p-value. The p-value tells us how likely it is to observe a result at least as extreme as ours if the null hypothesis were true.\n",
        "\n",
        "Although this procedure is often referred to as a “t-test,” in this setting it is closer to a z-test. This is because our data are Bernoulli rather than Normally distributed, and we rely on the CLT for approximate Normality. In large samples, the difference between the t-distribution and the standard Normal distribution is very small, so this distinction has little practical impact.\n",
        "\n",
        "Using the simulated data, I compute the test statistic and its corresponding p-value. If the p-value is small (for example, less than 0.05), this suggests that the observed difference is unlikely to be due to random chance, and we reject the null hypothesis. Otherwise, we do not have enough evidence to conclude that the two CTAs perform differently."
      ],
      "id": "ee76e0a3"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "theta_hat = np.mean(A) - np.mean(B)\n",
        "\n",
        "z = theta_hat / analytical_se\n",
        "\n",
        "p_value = 2 * (1 - norm.cdf(abs(z)))\n",
        "\n",
        "theta_hat, z, p_value"
      ],
      "id": "5dddf044",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## The T-Test as a Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "It turns out that the two-sample test we performed earlier is mathematically equivalent to a simple linear regression. This is useful because it shows that regression can be used not only for prediction, but also for hypothesis testing.\n",
        "\n",
        "To set this up, I combine the data from both groups into a single dataset. Each observation has an outcome $Y_i$, which is 1 if the visitor signed up and 0 otherwise, and an indicator variable $D_i$, which is 1 if the visitor saw CTA A and 0 if they saw CTA B. I then fit the following regression model:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$Y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 D_i + \\varepsilon_i$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The coefficients in this model have a clear interpretation. When $D_i = 0$ (CTA B), the expected value of $Y_i$ is $\\beta_0$, which corresponds to the average sign-up rate in group B, or $\\pi_B$. When $D_i = 1$ (CTA A), the expected value becomes $\\beta_0 + \\beta_1$, which corresponds to $\\pi_A$. Therefore, the coefficient $\\beta_1$ represents the difference between the two groups, so $\\beta_1 = \\pi_A - \\pi_B = \\theta$.\n",
        "\n",
        "This means that the OLS estimate $\\hat\\beta_1$ is exactly the same as the difference in sample means $\\hat\\theta = \\bar{X}_A - \\bar{X}_B$ that we computed earlier.\n",
        "\n",
        "After fitting the regression, I obtain estimates for $\\hat\\beta_1$, its standard error, t-statistic, and p-value. These results are very close to what we obtained using the two-sample test, with only small differences due to how the standard error is calculated.\n",
        "\n",
        "This equivalence is important because it shows that regression provides a flexible framework. In more complex settings, we can easily extend this model by adding more variables or interactions, while still using the same basic idea to estimate treatment effects."
      ],
      "id": "6dfe0ab6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import statsmodels.api as sm\n",
        "\n",
        "Y = np.concatenate([A, B])\n",
        "D = np.concatenate([np.ones(len(A)), np.zeros(len(B))])\n",
        "\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame({\"Y\": Y, \"D\": D})\n",
        "\n",
        "X = sm.add_constant(df[\"D\"])\n",
        "model = sm.OLS(df[\"Y\"], X).fit()\n",
        "\n",
        "model.summary()"
      ],
      "id": "6bbee2a7",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## The Problem with Peeking\n",
        "\n",
        "In practice, it can be tempting to check results before the experiment is finished. For example, instead of waiting until all 1,000 observations are collected, we might run the hypothesis test after every 100 observations and stop early if we find a significant result.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, this approach creates a problem under classical frequentist statistics. A single hypothesis test at the 5% significance level has a 5% chance of producing a false positive when the null hypothesis is true. But if we repeatedly check the results, each “peek” gives us another chance to incorrectly reject the null hypothesis. As a result, the overall probability of making at least one false rejection becomes much higher than 5%.\n",
        "\n",
        "To demonstrate this, I simulate a scenario where the null hypothesis is actually true, meaning $\\pi_A = \\pi_B = 0.20$ and there is no real difference between the two CTAs. For each simulated experiment, I draw 1,000 observations for each group and perform a hypothesis test after every 100 observations. I then record whether any of these tests produce a significant result at the 0.05 level.\n",
        "\n",
        "After repeating this process 10,000 times, I calculate the proportion of experiments where at least one false positive occurs. This gives an empirical estimate of the false positive rate when peeking is allowed.\n",
        "\n",
        "The results show that the false positive rate is much higher than the nominal 5%. This demonstrates that peeking inflates the Type I error rate. In practice, this means that stopping an experiment early based on repeated testing can lead to incorrect conclusions. To avoid this problem, it is important to predefine the sample size or use proper methods designed for sequential testing."
      ],
      "id": "288438a1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "def run_experiment():\n",
        "    A = np.random.binomial(1, 0.20, 1000)\n",
        "    B = np.random.binomial(1, 0.20, 1000)\n",
        "\n",
        "    for n in range(100, 1001, 100):\n",
        "        A_n = A[:n]\n",
        "        B_n = B[:n]\n",
        "\n",
        "        theta_hat = np.mean(A_n) - np.mean(B_n)\n",
        "\n",
        "        pA = np.mean(A_n)\n",
        "        pB = np.mean(B_n)\n",
        "\n",
        "        se = np.sqrt((pA*(1-pA))/n + (pB*(1-pB))/n)\n",
        "\n",
        "        z = theta_hat / se\n",
        "        p_value = 2 * (1 - norm.cdf(abs(z)))\n",
        "\n",
        "        if p_value < 0.05:\n",
        "            return 1  # false positive\n",
        "\n",
        "    return 0  # no false positive\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "results = [run_experiment() for _ in range(10000)]\n",
        "\n",
        "false_positive_rate = np.mean(results)\n",
        "false_positive_rate"
      ],
      "id": "abe919d0",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    }
  ],
